goals.question: What is the relationship between source and target?
goals.visualization: Scatter plot of source vs target
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if there is any correlation between the source and target fields.

goals.question: What is the distribution of source?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the range and distribution of values in the source field.

goals.question: What is the distribution of target?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the range and distribution of values in the target field.

goals.question: What are the top 10 most common source values?
goals.visualization: Bar chart of top 10 source values
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us identify the most common source values and their frequency.

goals.question: What are the top 10 most common target values?
goals.visualization: Bar chart of top 10 target values
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us identify the most common target values and their frequency.

code:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.scatter(data['source'], data['target'])
    plt.xlabel('Source')
    plt.ylabel('Target')
    plt.title('What is the relationship between source and target?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.hist(data['source'], bins=30, color='blue', alpha=0.7, label='Source')
    plt.xlabel('Source')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of source?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.hist(data['target'], bins=30, color='blue', alpha=0.7)
    plt.axvline(data['target'].median(), color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=2, label=f"Median: {data['target'].median():.2f}")
    plt.xlabel('Target')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of target?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    top_10_sources = data['source'].value_counts().head(10)
    top_10_sources.plot(kind='bar', color='blue', legend=True)
    plt.title('What are the top 10 most common source values?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Source')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    top_10_targets = data['target'].value_counts().head(10)
    top_10_targets.plot(kind='bar', color='c', edgecolor='k')
    plt.title('What are the top 10 most common target values?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Target Values')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.legend(['Top 10 Target Values'])
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
